<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Select Committee Inquiry: Future of the BBC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Northern Ireland Screen</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> [FBB0092]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary Points</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC plays a vital role within society, and remains to a large extent the envy of the world, underpinning or contributing to, many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aspects of society, including the UK’s pre-eminence in the creative industries.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Much of the BBC’s institutional stability and independence derives from the Licence Fee as its funding model.   While this model remains viable, it should be maintained.  Howe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ver, this extremely privileged funding mechanism places a heavy responsibility on the BBC to efficiently deliver public value to the whole of the UK.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s Public Purposes broadly reflect the BBC’s important position within society but during this C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">harter Period the BBC has fallen short of delivering fully against these Public Purposes in Northern Ireland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In particular, the BBC’s contribution to Stimulating Creativity and Cultural Excellence fell short in Northern Ireland with the ‘Out of London’ C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ommissioning Strategy having limited impact and the lack of a strategy plan for a sustainable contribution to Stimulating Creativity and Cultural Excellence very evident.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The BBC Trust’s Annual Performance Remit Survey also captured ongoing evidence that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the BBC does not fulfil its obligation to ‘Represent the UK, its nations and communities’ as relates to Northern Ireland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In Northern Ireland Screen’s experience, the BBC is a complex and challenging organisation with which to partner on any given project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  This day to day reality sits uncomfortably with the statement that ‘The BBC exists to serve the public interest.’  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland Screen would strongly support a rationalisation of the 25% external production quota and the Window of Creative Competi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tion into a simpler 45-50% external production quota.  While there is a strong argument for retaining the delivery of journalism and current affairs within the BBC, in Northern Ireland Screen’s experience, Stimulating Creativity and Cultural Excellence, Re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">presenting the UK, its nations, regions and communities, and Bringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK can all be better served through increased independent programme supply.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While the BBC’s independence is critical to its role in sustaining citizenship and civil society, the BBC Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State may not appropriately recognise the changed nature of the UK and, in particular, devolution in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Delivery &amp; Focus on Public Purposes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland Screen acts as the champion o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f the screen industry in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland and holds a remit on behalf of the Executive in Northern Ireland to maximise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the economic, cultural and educational value of the screen industries</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  In this role, Northern Ireland Screen holds responsibilities and obligations that are synergistic with the responsibilities that the BBC holds for the UK including Northern Ireland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As a consequence, Northern Ireland Screen collaborates with the BBC on many programming, sectoral and public value projects and initiatives.  We committed over £11 million to programming collaborations involving the BBC over the last 4 years.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our experie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nce from this many-faceted relationship informs the following observations:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland Screen has a very strong collaborative relationship with the   management of BBC Northern Ireland who share our ambition for Northern Ireland including in particu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lar our ambition for Northern Ireland to have a thriving and sustainable film &amp; television industry.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite our strong relationship with BBC Northern Ireland, we find dealing with the BBC challenging at a number of levels.  In our view, this is often t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he result of a centralised organisation with a very narrow and often hierarchical focus.  Beyond the BBC Northern Ireland management, we have a limited sense that the Public Purposes laid out in the Charter are strongly applied to the day to day activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The implementation of BBC plans whether they relate to the ‘Out of London’         Review, its archive strategy or how it contributes to Promoting Education or Learning is rarely transparent and easily understood.  There is very little sense </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that the views of stakeholders in Northern Ireland, whether in the BBC or outside of the BBC, have any impact on BBC plans or strategies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our experience is that the focus is usually on re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">latively narrowly defined BBC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">interests with limited regard for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Public Purposes and how the licence fee can best be utilised to maximise public value in association with partner organisations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A notable exception to these criticisms is the BBC’s support and partnership in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">delivering Public Value from the Irish Lan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">guage Broadcast Fund and Ulster-Scots </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Broadcast Fund.  BBC Northern Ireland has worked hard and constructively on making these Public Service funds (financed by DCMS and delivered through Northern Ireland Screen via the BFI) a success.  We note that this s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uccessful partnership is delivered at a local level within BBC Northern Ireland with limited reference to centralised support services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Independent Programme Supply stronger on Public Purposes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In Northern Ireland Screen’s experience, the Public Purpose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s already set for the BBC are served particularly well by programme supply from the independent sector.  For example, the stand out contributions in recent times could be the following, all from the independent sector:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cultural Excellence could be best ex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emplified by the Oscar won by Terry and Orla George for the short film </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Shore.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Representing the UK, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its nations, regions and communities could be best exemplified by Artists Studios’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Fall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the first BBC commissioned returning drama ever to portray </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bringing the UK to the world by the feature film </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Good Vibrations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">independently     </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">produced but supported by BBC films.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Promoting Education &amp; Learning might be best exemplified by Waddell Media’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Fables, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a co-commission between BBC No</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rthern Ireland and the Ulster-Scots Broadcast Fund.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Independent companies are also much better placed to lever other funding, to access international markets, and to drive swift change in to the screen industry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is for these reasons that Northern Irel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and Screen advocates an increase in the external production quota to 45-50%. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Simple &amp; Transparent Strategy to Deliver Public Purposes in the Northern Ireland</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcomed the ambitious Network Supply Strategy agreed in 2007 to establish 8 sustainable Creative Centres of Excellence throughout the UK. However, this has not been delivered in Northern Ireland due to, the lack of a strategy to develop Belfast as a pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oduction Centre of Excellence and to drive through the targets contained in the `Out of London’ commissioning strategy. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We note that the North of England, Scotland and Wales have each received extremely dramatic `forced distribution’ of network televisi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on production and very considerable investment in infrastructure.  Northern Ireland has received neither.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Without a strategy linked to the Public Purposes and targeting Northern Ireland, it is difficult to imagine how the BBC can either deliver strongly a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gainst the Public Purposes within or for Northern Ireland or be held properly accountable for those Public Purposes.  A third issue, very directly relevant to Northern Ireland Screen, is that it makes it difficult for potential partner organisations to ali</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gn with that strategy and for the BBC to constructively engage with those potential partners.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This weakness in partnership delivery has significant impact beyond programme production and broadcast.  The Promoting Education and Learning public purpose can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">only be delivered in partnership and those partnerships have to be local to Northern Ireland given the different education provision in Northern Ireland.  Northern Ireland Screen is at the forefront of digital media and moving image education</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but yet no r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eal strategic alliance exists between Northern Ireland Screen and the BBC.  The Public Purpose Promoting Education and Learning would suggest very clearly that it should.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Governance &amp; Accountability for Public Purposes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Northern Ireland Screen strongly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">supports the critical need for the BBC to be independent of government whether that is at a UK or devolved level. In that regard ten year intervals for Charter review is the right time period. Continual or more frequent reviews of the Charter would damage </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the independence of the BBC.  Our support of the need for this independence is one of the key drivers behind our support of the license fee mechanism of funding the BBC.  This semi arms length method of funding does underpin and emphasise the independence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The previous Governance model was shown to be imperfect and the current model has been shown not to serve the public interest in at least some respects. Lack of clarity between the BBC Trust and Executive on where responsibility sits for issue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s such as senior salaries, and who deals with what when things go wrong, demonstrate a weakness in the current model. This needs to be addressed if public confidence is to be regained. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Our experience is that the ambitions articulated by the BBC Trust do n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ot always translate into cohesive plans by the Executive. This structure should be addressed in Charter renewal, perhaps returning to a unitary Board model with a more detached form of regulation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At a more local level, the Charter renewal must still addr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ess the absence of effective accountability to Northern Ireland for the delivery of the BBC’s Public Purposes as they relate to Northern Ireland.  There are many layers to this – at a legislative level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where there may be a need for the devolved administrat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ions to have input into the BBC Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State; at BBC Trust level where the voice of the nations may require strengthening; and at BBC Executive level where the nations may not be strongly enough represented at the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Executive Board or indeed by Non Executive Directors.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Beyond these layers of governance and accountability, Northern Ireland Screen identifies the biggest weakness as being a simple and transparent strategy for Northern Ireland that is not only available</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for scrutiny by those responsible for governance, but is available as a road map and empowering authority for the many executives in the BBC an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d in BBC Northern Ireland who will ultimately deliver the activities that make up the BBC’s contribution to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Public Interest in Northern Ireland.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Northern Ireland Screen is the lead agency in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> for the film, television and digital content industry.  It is supported by the Department of Culture, Arts &amp; Leisure and the Department of Enterprise, Trade and Investment in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> and manages Language funds on behalf of the Department of Cultu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">re, Media &amp; Sport.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Northern Ireland Screen is best known as the agency which attracted HBO’s Game of Thrones to be produced in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The BFI rated Northern Ireland Screen’s framework for screen education the best in Europe</span></p></body></html>